<div id="comment_status_64589493" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64589493" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64589493" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64589493" name="comment_link_64589493" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23371771&amp;cid=64589493" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64589493)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64589493" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64589493); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Quantum+gravity">Quantum gravity</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Quantum+gravity">( 2576857 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64589493"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64589493">Absolute vacuum has no temperature at all, just as it has no taste or color.
<br> <br>
In nearly empty space, heat can be radiated and absorbed through radiation. Earth's is heated by the sun's radiation, to about 14 degrees Celsius.
<br> <br>
But an astronaut in the Earth's shadow can only absorb heat from distant stars and galaxies,
which is much less than what he emits.
Eventually, without solar radiation, his temperature will drop to the average space temperature in space of 2.7 Kelvin.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64589493">

</div>
</div>

<div id="replyto_64589493"></div>

