	<div id="comment_top_64588667" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64588667" name="comment_link_64588667" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23371771&amp;cid=64588667" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64588667)" >What about repairs and maintenance and safety.  </a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64588667" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64588667); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Retired+Chemist">Retired Chemist</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Retired+Chemist">( 5039029 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64588667">		
		on Saturday June 29, 2024 @06:48PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23371771&amp;cid=64588667">#64588667</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64588667">Are you just going to throw them away, when they stop working?  How often would they have to be replaced?

Solar power is available, but the size of the solar panels necessary to power a data center in space would be immense and do you really want a high-powered nuclear reactor orbiting overhead.

Cooling would be an issue as well.  Space is cold but has little ability to absorb heat.  Cooling would be by radiation, which is very inefficient and of course the reactor, if you used one, would generate a great deal of excess heat.

The whole idea seems very half-baked.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64588667">
