<div id="comment_64590167" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64590167" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64590167" name="comment_link_64590167" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23371771&amp;cid=64590167" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64590167)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64590167" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64590167); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Chelloveck">Chelloveck</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Chelloveck">( 14643 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64590167"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64590167"><blockquote><div><p>RTT/Latency: At 3.34s/1000m that's 4.7sec each way, or an RTT of 9.4sec.</p></div></blockquote><p>Looks like you dropped a prefix somewhere.  It takes 3.34 <em> <strong>micro</strong> </em>seconds for light to travel 1000m, giving a RTT of 9.4 milliseconds. Of course, that's only if the satellite is directly above the receiver.

</p><p>For comparison, I have Starlink. Starlink satellites orbit at about 550km. There's no noticeable lag on video calls. RTT ping time from here to slashdot.org is about 35ms, and that's 4 one-way trips between ground and the satellite.<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64590167">

